XII. ¹ Innocentia pro malivolentia] By innocentia in this place, we are to understand abstinence from the base, oppressive, and wicked methods of amassing riches, then in fashion. Such was the degeneracy of the times, that any person who did abstain and keep himself clear from these prevailing corruptions, was thought to do SO, not from a

love of virtue, or principle of integrity, but out of spite against, and in opposition to, those who fell in with them3 and that in order to cast reproach upon them and their way, and blacken their character by the lustre of his example. And this Ι take to be the import of the word malevolentia—M.
